          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Troop transfer</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-dec-20-1.jpg" alt="Troop transfer" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The ousting of Assad has put Russia in a complicated predicament. Russia previously said it was going to step back from Syria, but not away ultimately. However, the new transitional government has told Russia to <a href="https://www.euronews.com/2024/12/16/theres-no-reason-for-russian-troop-presence-in-syria-syrias-new-transitional-government" target="_blank">reconsider</a> its troops there. It has not overruled having relations with any country but wants to distance itself from those close to Assad. The transitional government also mentioned that it is open to dialogue with all countries to lay the new Syrian future.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Russia has depended on the Khmeimim Air Base and the Tartus Naval Base as they provide crucial access to the Mediterranean. Now, Russian troops have been massively withdrawn from Syria, and there is <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/russian-military-moving-from-syria-to-libya/a-71097602" target="_blank">speculation</a> that they could move a lot of their military presence to Libya. This brings a new era and set of challenges. Suppose Russia moves its military bases to Libya, it brings about a new recalibration of Russia‚Äôs strategy toward North Africa. It could lead to intensified competition with NATO and a potential escalation of conflict in Libya.‚Äã</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>


