          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Dexit in consideration</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">With just a couple of months ahead of the German elections, Alternative for Germany (AfD) has made a case for "<a href="https://www.dw.com/en/far-right-afd-party-wants-germany-to-leave-the-eu/a-71093400" target="_blank">Dexit</a>," which means Germany's withdrawal from the European Union (EU) and the eurozone. This shows the expansion of the AfD's nationalist and Euroskeptic stance despite widespread opposition from the German public, economic experts, and industry leaders. The AfD has some alternatives, such as "Europe of Fatherlands," a loose economic and interest community with a shared market but no overarching EU institutions.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Germany is one of the EU's most significant members and its economic center. While this would be an unthinkable move, the likelihood of it happening is relatively low because German EU membership is anchored in its constitution. Germans, even those who vote right-wing, are <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/eu-nato-growing-in-popularity-in-germany/a-68749726" target="_blank">pro-EU</a>. Movements like this are also gaining ground in the <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/hungary-and-the-netherlands-want-to-exit-eu-asylum-policy/a-70278674" target="_blank">Benelux</a> and <a href="https://fortune.com/2024/06/18/france-elections-emmanuel-macron-european-union-debt-economy-inflation-unemployment/" target="_blank">France</a>.</p>
        </mj-text>
