          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>üá∏üáæ Syria:</strong>   
          Israel's plan to <a href="https://www.euronews.com/2024/12/15/israel-approves-plans-to-up-golan-heights-settler-numbers-as-new-front-opens-in-syria" target="_blank">increase</a> settler numbers in the Golan Heights has drawn sharp criticism amid Syria's ongoing instability following the fall of President Bashar al-Assad. Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu announced a $ 10.3 million initiative to double settler numbers in territory annexed in 1981. While Netanyahu emphasized that Israel seeks no conflict with Syria, the plan was condemned by Saudi Arabia and Qatar as a violation of international law and a threat to regional stability.  While this plan doesn‚Äôt go that far out of Israel‚Äôs borders, the expansion plays into what many call the ‚ÄúGreater Israel" plan.</p>
