          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What is Greater Israel? </h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-dec-20-3.jpg" alt="What is Greater Israel?" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">"Greater Israel" refers to a concept that some people believe or advocate for regarding the <a href="https://theweek.com/world-news/what-is-the-greater-israel-movement" target="_blank">territorial expansion</a> of the State of Israel. It is most often associated with the idea that Israel should control a larger area than it currently does, encompassing all or parts of territories biblically significant to Jews. Some include the West Bank and parts of neighboring countries like Jordan, Lebanon, and Syria.‚Äã</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Critics of this concept say it undermines the right to a Palestinian state and turns the peace process upside down. Also, this term has been used by anti-semitic people to play into <a href="https://www.worldjewishcongress.org/en/conspiracy-myths/the-myth-that-jews-control-the-world" target="_blank">conspiracy theories</a> claiming the Jewish people own the world.  It's important to note that "Greater Israel" is not an official policy of the Israeli government but rather a viewpoint held by specific right-wing and religious groups.‚Äã</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
